title: For Sale:  Browning BDA 380
postcontent:
Browning BDA .380

Includes two 13-round magazines (of unknown mfgr.), no box.

The Browning BDA 380 was produced under contract by Beretta from 1977 - 1997, with a few special orders since then.  The BDA for sale here was made in 1981, the year Ronald Reagan became president.  This pistol is in very good condition.  The crappy photos below don't do it justice.


These were pretty cool for concealed-carry guns in the 1970s, 1980s, and into the 1990s.  Since there are now smaller 9mm and .380 guns, the niche for something like this is either (1) somebody who just likes "old school" guns made out of metal instead of plastic, or (2) somebody who is extremely recoil-sensitive, since a "larger" .380-caliber pistol is usually easier to shoot than a small 9mm pistol, or a .380 caliber "pocket pistol" (this varies from person to person, since felt recoil is a subjective).

In Europe, the Browning BDA 380 was sold as the Model 140 by Fabrique Nationale (FN) to police departments, in an era when some police departments around the world still issued .32 and .380 caliber pistols as primary duty weapons. 

Per Colorado law, the transfer must be conducted at an FFL dealer.  The buyer is responsible for all transfer fees.

I'm not looking for anything specific, but if you have an item to trade, feel free to ask.  The worst I can say is "No thanks, I'm not interested."   I also have more pictures of this gun if you want to see.  Armslist only lets me post three, so e-mail me for them.


The Browning BDA 380 is based on the Beretta 84 "Cheetah", and uses the same magazines as the Beretta 84.  Mec-Gar brand magazines are available for around $20 from  CDNN, Bud's Gun Shop, Gun Clips Depot, Top Gun Supply, and 44 Mag.  Just be sure to look under both "Beretta" and "Browning" magazines on those web sites.

Or you can search the internet for the item #
Mec-Gar 13-round Beretta 84 magazine, item # MGPB8413
Mec-Gar 13-round Browning BDA 380 magazine, item # MGBRBDA13

* BDLs have a baseplate, and ADLs do not. This means that the BDL has a "hinged magazine floorplate," enabling the user to unload the firearm without cycling the bolt. 
* BDLs have a unique fore-end cap that acts as a recoil buffer.

The P238 is built on an anodized alloy beavertail style frame with a flat dark earth finish, Hogue Piranha G-10 grips with matching G-10 main spring housing. The stainless steel slide features the popular trademarked Sig Sauer slide serrations, flat dark earth finish and SIGLITE Night Sights. 7 round extended magazine.

The vest was tested to stop a 9 mm 124 grain full metal jacket bullet at 1,400 ft/s (426 m/s) with minimal deformation and has a V-50 of roughly 1,525 ft/s (465 m/s). This means that the bullet has to be traveling faster than 1,525 ft/s for it to have more than a 50% chance of breaking through the soft armor panel. 
These soft ballistic panels are size Large, which are installed into their respective pocket on the vest carrier shell.
